page.content: { 16:}From this ridge you can see into THORNCOMBE WOOD where RHODODENDRON is spreading. The YELLOW HAMMER is a heathland bird found here whilst LINNETS and sometimes REDPOLLS are winter visitors. { 17:}This BIRCH is infected by a fungus which produces abnormal clusters of twigs known as WITCHES BROOMS. { 18:}Under the dense shade of the BEECH little vegetation grows, but a great variety of FUNGI can be seen in Autumn living in the leaf litter. Beech seeds are food for such creatures as PHEASANTS, PIGEONS and WOODMICE. The nearby hollows are SWALLET HOLES, formed by the slow erosion of underlying layers of chalk by acidic water passing through from the surface gravels.
